      "author_association" : "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body" : "Looks for me like the code below is the starting point of `onlynet` argument parsing. Is it right that `onlynet` can be specified multiple times to allow multiple networks? If yes, I think that should be mentioned in the CLI argument documentation (extend #13418).\r\nWith the following in `bitcoin.conf`:\r\n```\r\nonlynet=ipv4\r\nonlynet=ipv6\r\n```\r\nthe node connects outgoing via IPv4, which seemed it was not doing with a single `onlynet=ipv6`\r\n\r\nCould someone point me to, where `NET_MAX`, used in the second for loop, is set to a value? I did search for \"NET_MAX\" in the repository, but did not find where it would be set to a value. Thanks.\r\n\r\n`src/init.cpp`\r\n```\r\nif (gArgs.IsArgSet(\"-onlynet\")) {\r\n        std::set<enum Network> nets;\r\n        for (const std::string& snet : gArgs.GetArgs(\"-onlynet\")) {\r\n            enum Network net = ParseNetwork(snet);\r\n            if (net == NET_UNROUTABLE)\r\n                return InitError(strprintf(_(\"Unknown network specified in -onlynet: '%s'\"), snet));\r\n            nets.insert(net);\r\n        }\r\n        for (int n = 0; n < NET_MAX; n++) {\r\n            enum Network net = (enum Network)n;\r\n            if (!nets.count(net))\r\n                SetLimited(net);\r\n        }\r\n}\r\n```",
      "created_at" : "2018-06-21T03:25:47Z",
